 Other comments: 



the youthful journey of Michał Jan Borch started in 1774, and not in 1772, as the author states (pp. 3-4);



the conversion of Polish-Livonian Borch family members to Catholicism had already started by the end of the 17th century, so in the case of this family the whole phenomenon should be dated for from the turn of the 17th/18th century (p. 5);



what is meant by the term "magistrate" requires clarification, which specific office/dignity is meant in this case? During his journey Michał Jan Borch happened to use various titles illegally, presenting himself as a "major-general" (amongst other titles), although he never achieved this rank during his military "career". Maybe in this case he actually assigned himself the office illegally, or the mistake was made on the part of the Vatican officials occurred? (pp. 10-11).
